Claims CLAIMS: 1. A non-transitory computer-readable medium storing instructions readable and executable by at least one electronic processor (20) to perform an atrial fibrillation (AF) detection method (100), the method comprising: generating a time-frequency representation of an electrocardiogram (ECG) signal acquired over a time interval; processing the time-frequency representation using a neural network (N ) (32) to output probabilities for rhythms of a set of rhythms including at least atrial fibrillation; assigning a rhythm for the ECG signal based on the probabilities for the rhythms of the set of rhythms output by the neural network; and controlling a display device (24) to display the rhythm assigned to the ECG signal. 2. The non-transitory computer-readable medium of claim 1, wherein the set of rhythms includes at least: a normal sinus rhythm; atrial fibrillation; and another rhythm which is not a normal sinus rhythm and is not atrial fibrillation. 3. The non-transitory computer-readable medium of claim 2, wherein the set of rhythms includes atrial fibrillation, normal sinus rhythm, and an other rhythm which is not atrial fibrillation and is not normal sinus rhythm, and the assigning includes: responsive to the probabilities output by the neural network for the normal sinus rhythm and the an other rhythm being within a similarity threshold of each other, applying a secondary classifier to select the rhythm for assignment from between the normal sinus rhythm and the other rhythm. 4. The non-transitory computer-readable medium of any one of claims 1-3 wherein the 

 set of rhythms includes at least: a normal sinus rhythm; atrial fibrillation; and a noisy recording. 5. The non-transitory computer-readable medium of any one of claims 1-3, wherein the processing includes choosing a neural network (32) for use in the processing on the basis of a time length of the ECG signal from at least two different neural networks respectively trained on sets of ECG signal segments of different time lengths. 6. The non-transitory computer-readable medium of any one of claims 1-5, wherein the generating of the time-frequency representation of the ECG signal comprises: generating the time-frequency representation with values of a time dimension indexing time windows of a sliding time window over the ECG signal and with, for each indexed time window, values along a frequency dimension representing a frequency spectrum of the portion of the ECG signal in the indexed time window. 7. The non-transitory computer-readable medium of claim 6, wherein the frequency spectrum of the portion of the ECG signal in the indexed time window is a spectrogram or wavelet spectrum. 8. The non-transitory computer-readable medium of any one of claims 1-7, wherein the method further includes: determining a signal quality index (SQI) of the ECG signal over the time interval; wherein the assigning includes assigning a noisy recording for the ECG signal if the determined SQI is below the preselected SQI threshold. 9. The non-transitory computer-readable medium of claim 8, wherein the method does not perform the processing using the neural network if the determined SQI is below the preselected SQI threshold. 10. The non-transitory computer-readable medium of any one of claims 1-9, wherein the NN (32) is a Convolutional NN (CNN). 1 1. The non-transitory computer-readable medium of claim 10, wherein the CNN (32) is a Densely Connected CNN which, for each layer of the CNN, concatenates all preceding layer feature-maps as input. 12. The non-transitory computer-readable medium of any one of claims 1-11 , wherein the method further includes: controlling an electrocardiograph measurement device (12) to acquire the ECG signal over a single data acquisition time period and then to stop acquisition of the ECG signal. 13. The non-transitory computer-readable medium of any one of claims 1-11 , wherein the method further includes: controlling an electrocardiograph measurement device (12) to continuously acquire ECG signal data; wherein the ECG signal acquired over the time interval is the segment of the continuously acquired ECG signal data which is acquired over the time interval. 14. A device (10) for detecting atrial fibrillation, the device comprising: an electrocardiogram (ECG) measurement device (12) with one or more leads (14) having one or more electrodes (16) attachable to a patient; at least one electronic processor (20, 30) programmed to: control the ECG measurement device (12) to acquire an ECG signal over a single data acquisition time period and then to stop acquisition of the ECG signal; generate a time-frequency representation of the ECG signal acquired over a time interval with values of a time dimension indexing time windows of a sliding time window over the ECG signal and with, for each indexed time window, values along a frequency dimension representing a frequency spectrum of the portion of the ECG signal in the indexed time window; 

 process the time-frequency representation using a neural network (N ) (32) to output probabilities for rhythms of a set of rhythms including at least atrial fibrillation; assign a rhythm for the ECG signal based on the probabilities for the rhythms of the set of rhythms output by the neural network; and control a display device (24) to display the rhythm assigned to the ECG signal. 15. The device (10) of claim 14, wherein the set of rhythms includes at least: a normal sinus rhythm; atrial fibrillation; another rhythm which is not a normal sinus rhythm and is not atrial fibrillation; and a noisy recording. 16. The device (10) of claim 15, wherein the at least one electronic processor (20, 30) is further programmed to: responsive to the probabilities output by the neural network for the normal sinus rhythm and the an other rhythm being within a similarity threshold of each other, apply a secondary classifier to select the rhythm for assignment from between the normal sinus rhythm and the other rhythm. 17. The device (10) of any one of claims 14-16, wherein the at least one electronic processor (20, 30) is further programmed to: choosing a neural network (32) for use in the processing on the basis of a time length of the ECG signal from at least two different neural networks respectively trained on sets of ECG signal segments of different time lengths. 18. An atrial fibrillation (AF) detection method (100), comprising: acquiring an electrocardiograph (ECG) signal with an ECG measurement device (12); 

 determining a signal quality index (SQI) of the ECG signal over the time interval; generating a time-frequency representation of the ECG signal acquired over a time interval with values of a time dimension indexing time windows of a sliding time window over the ECG signal and with, for each indexed time window, values along a frequency dimension representing a frequency spectrum of the portion of the ECG signal in the indexed time window; processing the time-frequency representation using a neural network (N ) (32) to output probabilities for rhythms of a set of rhythms including at least atrial fibrillation, a normal sinus rhythm, another rhythm which is not a normal sinus rhythm and is not atrial fibrillation, and a noisy recording; assigning a rhythm for the ECG signal based on the probabilities for the rhythms of the set of rhythms output by the neural network; and controlling a display device (24) to display the rhythm assigned to the ECG signal. 19. The method (100) of claim 18, further including: responsive to the probabilities output by the neural network for the normal sinus rhythm and the an other rhythm being within a similarity threshold of each other, applying a secondary classifier to select the rhythm for assignment from between the normal sinus rhythm and the other rhythm. 20. The method (100) of claim 18, further including: performing the determining with at least one electronic processor (20); and assigning a rhythm of noise of the ECG signal when the SQI is below a preselected SQI threshold; and when the SQI is above the preselected SQI threshold, performing the generating, processing, and assigning with a cloud computing server (30).
